# Multi-Agent Coordination

## ⚠️ CRITICAL: Agent Specialization & Coordination ⚠️

**This rule enables multiple AI agents to work together efficiently on the same project while maintaining code quality and preventing conflicts.**

## Agent Roles & Specialization

### **Agent 1: Core Systems Specialist**
**Focus**: Complex business logic, data operations, AI integration, algorithms
**Skills**: Advanced programming, data structures, API integration, complex problem-solving
**Complexity**: High-complexity work that requires deep technical expertise

### **Agent 2: User Experience Specialist**
**Focus**: User interface, design, user interactions, usability, accessibility
**Skills**: UI/UX design, frontend development, user psychology, visual design
**Complexity**: User-facing work that requires design thinking and user empathy

### **Agent 3: Quality & Infrastructure**
**Focus**: Testing, build systems, deployment, optimization, documentation
**Skills**: Testing frameworks, build tools, DevOps, performance optimization
**Complexity**: Quality assurance and infrastructure work

## File Ownership & Boundaries

### **Project Configuration**
- Each project has a configuration file defining file ownership
- Agents own specific files based on their specialization
- Clear boundaries prevent editing conflicts
- Coordination points defined for integration

### **Ownership Rules**
- **Own Files**: Full read/write access to assigned files
- **Other Files**: Read-only access for understanding context
- **Coordination**: Changes affecting multiple agents require coordination
- **Respect Boundaries**: Never edit files owned by other agents

### **Emergency Override**
- **Agent Unavailable**: Other agents can take over abandoned files
- **Critical Bugs**: Any agent can fix critical issues in any file
- **Document Changes**: Always document cross-boundary changes

## Coordination Protocols

### **Git Communication**
- **Commit Format**: `[AGENT_ROLE] Description of changes`
- **Integration Points**: Document how changes affect other agents
- **Status Updates**: Regular commits showing progress
- **Questions**: Use Git commits or issues for clarification

### **Handoff Process**
1. **Prepare Handoff**: Current agent documents current state
2. **Generate Handoff Prompt**: Structured prompt for receiving agent
3. **Transfer Ownership**: Update project state and file ownership
4. **Coordinate Integration**: Ensure smooth transition

### **Handback Process**
1. **Complete Work**: Finishing agent documents completed work
2. **Generate Handback Prompt**: Structured prompt for original agent
3. **Integration Testing**: Receiving agent tests integration
4. **Resume Ownership**: Original agent resumes full control

## Integration with Existing Rules

### **All Existing Rules Apply**
- **Enhanced Error Handling**: All agents follow error handling standards
- **Code Quality Standards**: All agents maintain quality standards
- **Perchance Best Practices**: All agents understand platform constraints
- **Communication Style**: All agents use same communication style
- **Context Management**: All agents respect context limits
- **Basic Security**: All agents follow security practices

### **Rule Adaptations**
- **Mode Control**: Agents can be in different modes (Plan/Act)
- **Core Startup**: Primary agent runs full startup, others run lightweight
- **Error Handling**: Agents coordinate error resolution
- **Quality Standards**: Agents review each other's work

## Agent Availability & Fallbacks

### **Single Agent Mode (Default)**
- **One Agent**: Handles all aspects of development
- **Full Ownership**: Owns all files and responsibilities
- **Standard Rules**: Follows all existing rules normally

### **Multi-Agent Mode**
- **Multiple Agents**: Each handles their specialization
- **Shared Ownership**: Files divided by expertise
- **Coordination**: Regular communication and handoffs

### **Agent Unavailable**
- **Graceful Degradation**: Other agents can take over
- **Emergency Mode**: Any agent can edit any file if critical
- **Recovery**: System returns to stable state

## Success Criteria

### **Effective Coordination**
- **Clear Communication**: All agents understand their roles
- **No Conflicts**: File ownership prevents editing conflicts
- **Quality**: All agents maintain same quality standards
- **Efficiency**: Parallel work when possible, coordination when needed

### **Project Success**
- **Feature Completion**: All features implemented completely
- **Quality Standards**: All code meets quality requirements
- **Integration**: All components work together seamlessly
- **Documentation**: All changes documented appropriately

## Troubleshooting

### **Common Issues**
- **File Conflicts**: Check project configuration and ownership
- **Communication Gaps**: Use Git commits for coordination
- **Quality Inconsistencies**: Ensure all agents follow same rules
- **Integration Problems**: Test coordination points regularly

### **Escalation**
- **Major Conflicts**: Human coordination required
- **Technical Blocks**: Agent consultation needed
- **Process Issues**: Review and update coordination protocols
